				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/22/opinion/9222014chavez/9222014chavez-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/22/opinion/9222014chavez/9222014chavez-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/22/opinion/9222014chavez/9222014chavez-blog480.jpg" id="100000003130546" width="480" height="303" alt="Maria Gabriela Chavez and President Nicolas Maduro in Caracas, on April 19, 2013."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="303"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Maria Gabriela Chavez and President Nicolas Maduro in Caracas, on April 19, 2013.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Fernando Llano/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There could be major drama on the United Nations Security Council next year if, as widely expected, Venezuela gets a seat adjacent to that of its nemesis, the United States, to represent Latin American and Caribbean nations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Venezuelaâs socialist government is chummy with Iran and Russia and would likely vote against, and rail about, American interests at every turn. This promises to be particularly contentious during a year in which the security council is likely to tackle major issues, including Russiaâs expansionist spree and Washingtonâs military campaign against Sunni extremist militants in Iraq and Syria.<br />
<span id="more-18067"></span><br />
To make matters worse, Venezuelaâs seat on the council could be occupied by MarÃ­a Gabriela ChÃ¡vez, the daughter of the countryâs late president, Hugo ChÃ¡vez, who was loud and brash in his criticism of the United States. (Some readers may recall the 2006 speech during which<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2006/09/20/world/americas/20cnd-chavez.html"> Chavez called President George W. Bush âthe devil,â</a> and said the podium where the American president had spoken the day before âsmells of sulphur still.â)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Because the seats on the council are arranged alphabetically, Chavezâs daughter is likely to end up sitting next to Samantha Power, the American envoy. Venezuelaâs current president, NicolÃ¡s Maduro, has accused the United States of nefariously interfering in his countryâs affairs &#8212; presenting no credible evidence. Earlier this year, he kicked out three American diplomats. So itâs quite likely Chavez and Power would wind up trading barbs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Considering Venezuelaâs atrocious crackdown on the opposition this year, and Maduroâs poisonous relationship with Washington, it might seem bewildering that Latin American and Caribbean nations would want to be represented by Venezuela on a highly-visible body.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But it was all preordained. Years ago, members of the of The Latin American and Caribbean Group negotiated a security council rotation that the 33 members formalize periodically through a vote. This year itâs Venezuelaâs turn.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">American officials successfully lobbied in 2006 to keep Venezuela off the council, making this yearâs likely ascension a triumph that the government in Caracas will relish. Despite widespread concern about Venezuelaâs human rights record and ailing economy, its neighbors recently signaled that they will not stand in the way. That annoys officials at the State Department to no end, but they have been measured in their criticism.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOur concerns with regard to Venezuelaâs record on human rights and democratic governance are well known,â the State Department said in an e-mailed statement. âAs we have said before, we believe all Security Council members and countries aspiring to be members should support the principles of the UN Charter, contribute to the Security Councilâs role in maintaining international peace and security, and uphold and advance human rights.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So far, Venezuela is running unopposed for the seat. But another country in the region could launch a last-minute candidacy, as the editorial board has urged. That would spare the world of petty theatrics on the council for the next couple of years.</p>
	</div>
